Step 1. Compute the Return on Equity (ROE) using the average owner's equity.  
• The beginning owner’s equity is given by Paid-in Capital (with no Retained Earnings at the beginning): 13,000,000.00  
• The ending owner’s equity is given: 10,964,263.48  
• Average Owner’s Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 10,964,263.48) / 2  
  = 23,964,263.48 / 2  
  ≈ 11,982,131.74  

The net profit (from the income statement) is –2,035,736.52.  

Thus, ROE = (Net Profit) / (Average Owner's Equity)  
  = –2,035,736.52 / 11,982,131.74  
  ≈ –0.1699 or –16.99%

Step 2. Compute the Debt to Asset Ratio.  
Liabilities come from the sum of the accounts shown under liabilities:  
• Accounts Payable = 1,260,000.00  
• Taxes Payable = 341,835.08  

Total Liabilities = 1,260,000.00 + 341,835.08 = 1,601,835.08  

Total Assets (end amount) = 12,566,098.56  

Thus, Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
  = 1,601,835.08 / 12,566,098.56  
  ≈ 0.1275 or about 0.13

Step 3. Compute the Gross Profit Margin.  
From the income statement:  
• Gross Profit = 1,136,701.10  
• Total Revenue = 6,836,701.10  

Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%  
  = (1,136,701.10 / 6,836,701.10) × 100%  
  ≈ 0.1663 × 100%  
  ≈ 16.63%

Thus, the final answers are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "-16.99%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.13",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "16.63%"
  }
}
